ground_truth:
To modify the `GenerateRandomCreature` function to ensure that no two abilities are the same in a single creature instance, we can simply use a `map` instead of a slice to keep track of the abilities that have already been generated, and continue generating abilities until we have three unique ones:

```go
func GenerateRandomCreature() *MagicalCreature {
 elements := []string{"fire", "water", "earth", "air"}
 abilities := []string{"teleportation", "shape-shifting", "invisibility", "mind-reading", "fire-breathing", "water-manipulation", "earthquake-generation", "flight"}
 creature := &MagicalCreature{}
 // Generate random name
 creature.Name = fmt.Sprintf("Creature-%d", rand.Intn(100))
 // Generate random element
 creature.Element = elements[rand.Intn(len(elements))]
 // Generate 3 unique random abilities
 abilityMap := make(map[string]bool)
 for len(abilityMap) < 3 {
 ability := abilities[rand.Intn(len(abilities))]
 abilityMap[ability] = true
 }
 creature.Abilities = make([]string, 0, len(abilityMap))
 for ability := range abilityMap {
 creature.Abilities = append(creature.Abilities, ability)
 }
 // Generate random description
 creature.Description = fmt.Sprintf("This %s creature is known for its %s abilities.", creature.Element, creature.Abilities)
 return creature
}
```

In this modified version of `GenerateRandomCreature`, we use a `map` called `abilityMap` to keep track of the abilities that have already been generated. We generate abilities until the `abilityMap` has three unique ones. Finally, we convert the `abilityMap` back into a slice and assign it to `creature.Abilities`.

