How can I write a C# program that calculates the difference between two given dates in years?
Here's a starter code:
DateTime givenDate = new DateTime(2015, 8, 12);
DateTime currentDate = DateTime.Today;
TimeSpan difference = currentDate - givenDate;
int years = (int)(difference.TotalDays / 365.25);
Console.WriteLine("The difference between the given date and today's date is: " + years + " years.");
You can replace the given date with any date of your choice. How can this code be optimized for better performance?

ground_truth:
The code you provided is already quite efficient, but there are a few optimizations you can make:
1. Instead of dividing by 365.25 to get the number of years, you can use the TotalDays property of the TimeSpan object and divide by the average number of days in a year (365.2425). This will give you a more accurate result.
2. You can use the TryParseExact method to parse the input dates, which will improve the performance and handle any formatting issues.
Here's an optimized version of the code:
DateTime givenDate;
DateTime currentDate = DateTime.Today;
if (DateTime.TryParseExact("2015-08-12", "yyyy-MM-dd", CultureInfo.InvariantCulture, DateTimeStyles.None, out givenDate))
{
 TimeSpan difference = currentDate - givenDate;
 int years = (int)(difference.TotalDays / 365.2425);
 Console.WriteLine("The difference between the given date and today's date is: " + years + " years.");
}
else
{
 Console.WriteLine("Invalid date format.");
}
You can replace the input date and format with any values of your choice.

